  "text": "Despite the apparent importance of the CC-CK class in atherosclerosis, recent studies have also provided strong evidence that other CK classes such as the CX 3 C and the CXC CKs also play important roles in atherosclerosis. CX 3 CL1, also known as fractalkine, and its receptor CX 3 CR1 are the only members of the CX 3 C CK class. Fractalkine is present in human atherosclerotic lesions, [CITATION_1] 27 and smooth muscle cells in the neointima of human atherosclerotic plaques express its receptor, CX 3 CR1. 27 Furthermore, 2 studies have shown that ApoE/CX 3 CR1 double-KO mice had significant reductions in lesion size in the proximal aorta and in the thoracic and abdominal descending aortas compared with ApoE KO control mice. [CITATION_2] 29 There is also evidence that the CXC class of CK, responsible for neutrophil chemotaxis, is important in atherosclerosis. Adoptive transfer of CXCR2 KO bone marrow was protective in mice with myocardial ischemia-reperfusion injury, leading to reductions in inflammatory cell infiltration and infarct size. 30 These potentially important contributions by other CK classes may limit the effectiveness of CC-CK blockade alone in atherosclerosis. Indeed, our previous work confirmed that 35K has no effect on fracktalkine/CX3CR1 signaling. 22 Future studies need to assess the relative importance of both CC and CXC CKs in atherosclerosis to identify the most promising therapeutic strategies.",
